To estimate the depth of SOL re-accumulated since the fire vs. residual SOL that predates the last fire, we measured the depth of the charcoal layer from the top of the SOL layer (in cm, excluding leaf litter, live moss or lichen). Charcoal layers were not always visible within SOL cores.

Since we sampled in July, some of the frozen soil we drilled is actually active layer and some is permafrost. We used our average September thaw depths from other studies to estimate frozen active layer depth cutoffs

Snow was collected and categorized as:
1. "s" surface snow. Sample was scraped from top 0.5 to 1 cm of surface.

3. "r" rime. Sample was collected from a fabric mesh and was either rime or frost.
4. A small number of yukimarimo snow samples were collected.

Standard deviation is a statistical measurement of variation in a set of data values. Each individual position reported here can be calculated many times over using different GPS satellite combinations in the processing, generating a set of values to best estimate the position as well as its accuracy. Because GPS measurements are typically less accurate in the vertical as compared to horizontal components, we report the standard deviation of each component separately.

Daily blanks were performed for one hour while the instrument was active. The median value of a day's blank was added back into that day's ozone observations, and its standard deviation was propagated into the measurement uncertainty. Note: The blank programming on O-Buoys 13 and 14 malfunctioned mid-deployment. Data for which a daily blank was not available are indicated by the "blank" column.
